{
  "texts": [
    "The Goodwillie derivatives assemble into a left adjoint𝜕 *: Exc 𝑑 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) -→ SymSeq, between the ∞-category of 𝑑-excisive functors and the ∞-category of symmetric sequences [AC15, Proposition 4.5].",
    "This functor factors through 𝑑-truncated symmetric sequences since 𝜕 𝑖 𝑃 𝑑 ≃ 0 for 𝑖 > 𝑑.",
    "The mapping spectra in symmetric sequences decompose as a product, so there is an induced map on mapping spectra𝜕 *: Hom Exc 𝑑 * (Sp 𝜔,Sp) (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S, 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) -→ 1≤𝑖≤𝑑 Hom Sp (𝜕 𝑖 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S), 𝜕 𝑖 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S)),which induces a ring map𝜃 𝑑: 𝜋 0 End Exc 𝑑 * (Sp 𝜔,Sp) (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) ⊗ Q -→ 1≤𝑖≤𝑑 𝜋 0 Hom Sp (𝜕 𝑖 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S), 𝜕 𝑖 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S)) ⊗ Q Q 𝑑on the level of rational homotopy categories, where the last isomorphism follows from Arone and Ching's computation [AC15, Lemma 5.10] of the derivatives of representables as 𝜕 𝑖 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) ≃ S with trivial Σ 𝑖 -action for all 1 ≤ 𝑖 ≤ 𝑑.To ease notation, we will denote the endomorphism ring 𝜋 0 Hom Sp (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S, 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) ⊗ Q by 𝑅 Q (𝑑).We will now show that Goodwillie-Burnside ring 𝐴 Q (𝑑) is isomorphic to this endomorphism ring 𝑅 Q (𝑑), by an intricate analysis of how the calculus and the Q-linear algebra interact.Lemma 5.1.",
    "There is an isomorphism𝑅 Q (𝑑) 𝐴 Q (𝑑)between the endomorphism ring of the monoidal unit in Exc 𝑑 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q and the rational Goodwillie-Burnside ring.Proof.",
    "There is a zigzag of ring maps𝑅 Q (𝑑) 𝜃 𝑑 ---→ Q 𝑑 𝜙 ← --𝐴 Q (𝑑),in which the right-most map is an isomorphism by Theorem 2.4, hence it suffices to show that𝜃 𝑑: 𝑅 Q (𝑑) → Q 𝑑 isan isomorphism."
  ]
